<subSubSection lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="391" pageId="12" pageNumber="390" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1731,2010]" lastBlockId="13.[151,1437,150,969]" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="391" pageId="12" pageNumber="390">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,297,1767,1793]" pageId="12" pageNumber="390">Nymph:</emphasis>
Mature male body length 
<quantity box="[597,718,1767,1794]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.85" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.7" pageId="12" pageNumber="390" unit="mm" value="18.5" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="17.0">17–20 mm</quantity>
(n = 3). Dorsum gray to olive green with some pale patterning; ventrally paler grey (
<figureCitation box="[384,522,1803,1830]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 24" captionStart-1="FIGURE 25" captionStartId-0="14.[151,250,1963,1987]" captionStartId-1="15.[151,250,951,975]" captionTargetBox-0="[158,1429,1147,1934]" captionTargetBox-1="[169,1416,187,922]" captionTargetId-0="figure-48@14.[154,1434,1142,1938]" captionTargetId-1="figure-30@15.[161,1426,181,927]" captionTargetPageId-0="14" captionTargetPageId-1="15" captionText-0="FIGURE 24. Perlodinella epiproctalis (Zwick, 1997), male nymph. A–B: head and thorax, dorsal and ventral view; C–D: abdomen, dorsal and ventral view." captionText-1="FIGURE 25. Perlodinella epiproctalis (Zwick, 1997), male nymph. A: mandible; B: lacinia; C: labium; D: epiproct; E: cercal segments." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810279" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810281" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/6810279/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/6810281/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="390">Figs. 24–25</figureCitation>
). Body covered by short colorless hairs. Head with a large pale spot in front of the anterior ocellus extending onto the clypeus; M-line indistinct; interocellar area brown with small pentagonal, central pale spot, closed posteriorly; occiput with a pair of oval pale spots around the epicranial stem bordered by sinuate brownish rows behind each eye (
<figureCitation box="[520,624,1911,1937]" captionStart="FIGURE 24" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1963,1987]" captionTargetBox="[158,1429,1147,1934]" captionTargetId="figure-48@14.[154,1434,1142,1938]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 24. Perlodinella epiproctalis (Zwick, 1997), male nymph. A–B: head and thorax, dorsal and ventral view; C–D: abdomen, dorsal and ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810279" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810279/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="390">Fig. 24A</figureCitation>
). Submental gills are short (
<figureCitation box="[938,1041,1911,1937]" captionStart="FIGURE 24" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1963,1987]" captionTargetBox="[158,1429,1147,1934]" captionTargetId="figure-48@14.[154,1434,1142,1938]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 24. Perlodinella epiproctalis (Zwick, 1997), male nymph. A–B: head and thorax, dorsal and ventral view; C–D: abdomen, dorsal and ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810279" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810279/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="390">Fig. 24B</figureCitation>
). Mandible bidentate, with 2 apical teeth and 3 subapical teeth; a patch of 15–18 hairs present ventral to the subapical teeth (
<figureCitation box="[1149,1254,1947,1974]" captionStart="FIGURE 25" captionStartId="15.[151,250,951,975]" captionTargetBox="[169,1416,187,922]" captionTargetId="figure-30@15.[161,1426,181,927]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 25. Perlodinella epiproctalis (Zwick, 1997), male nymph. A: mandible; B: lacinia; C: labium; D: epiproct; E: cercal segments." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810281/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="390">Fig. 25A</figureCitation>
). Lacinia bidentate, apically narrow, basal half expanded; 12–14 submarginal setae present; 2–3 setae present ventral to the base of the subapical tooth and 2–3 setae at the juncture of the apical teeth (
<figureCitation box="[960,1064,150,177]" captionStart="FIGURE 25" captionStartId="15.[151,250,951,975]" captionTargetBox="[169,1416,187,922]" captionTargetId="figure-30@15.[161,1426,181,927]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 25. Perlodinella epiproctalis (Zwick, 1997), male nymph. A: mandible; B: lacinia; C: labium; D: epiproct; E: cercal segments." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810281/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="391">Fig. 25B</figureCitation>
). Paraglossae flat and fingerlike; glossa wide and semicircular, apex slightly truncated, with thick fine hairs (
<figureCitation box="[993,1095,186,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 25" captionStartId="15.[151,250,951,975]" captionTargetBox="[169,1416,187,922]" captionTargetId="figure-30@15.[161,1426,181,927]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 25. Perlodinella epiproctalis (Zwick, 1997), male nymph. A: mandible; B: lacinia; C: labium; D: epiproct; E: cercal segments." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810281/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="391">Fig. 25C</figureCitation>
). Thoracic segments rectangular with wide, pale, median stripes. Male wingpads very short. Legs with few scattered brown spinules on surface (
<figureCitation box="[159,265,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 24" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1963,1987]" captionTargetBox="[158,1429,1147,1934]" captionTargetId="figure-48@14.[154,1434,1142,1938]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 24. Perlodinella epiproctalis (Zwick, 1997), male nymph. A–B: head and thorax, dorsal and ventral view; C–D: abdomen, dorsal and ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810279" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810279/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="391">Fig. 24A</figureCitation>
). Abdominal terga with two rows of large, oval, pale paramedial spots; spots are indistinct on tergum 10 (
<figureCitation box="[159,298,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURE 24" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1963,1987]" captionTargetBox="[158,1429,1147,1934]" captionTargetId="figure-48@14.[154,1434,1142,1938]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 24. Perlodinella epiproctalis (Zwick, 1997), male nymph. A–B: head and thorax, dorsal and ventral view; C–D: abdomen, dorsal and ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810279" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810279/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="391">Fig. 24C–D</figureCitation>
). All abdominal segments have a few short, stout spinules that become more numerous on the sterna 6–10. Epiproct is already visible on mature nymphs (
<figureCitation box="[739,843,330,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 25" captionStartId="15.[151,250,951,975]" captionTargetBox="[169,1416,187,922]" captionTargetId="figure-30@15.[161,1426,181,927]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 25. Perlodinella epiproctalis (Zwick, 1997), male nymph. A: mandible; B: lacinia; C: labium; D: epiproct; E: cercal segments." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810281/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="391">Fig. 25D</figureCitation>
). Paraprocts short, apex rounded (
<figureCitation box="[1220,1358,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 24" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1963,1987]" captionTargetBox="[158,1429,1147,1934]" captionTargetId="figure-48@14.[154,1434,1142,1938]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 24. Perlodinella epiproctalis (Zwick, 1997), male nymph. A–B: head and thorax, dorsal and ventral view; C–D: abdomen, dorsal and ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810279" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810279/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="391">Fig. 24C–D</figureCitation>
). Cerci with dorsal fringe of fine, silky, colorless hairs; each cercal segment with an apical whorl of short brown setae (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 25" captionStartId="15.[151,250,951,975]" captionTargetBox="[169,1416,187,922]" captionTargetId="figure-30@15.[161,1426,181,927]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 25. Perlodinella epiproctalis (Zwick, 1997), male nymph. A: mandible; B: lacinia; C: labium; D: epiproct; E: cercal segments." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810281/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="391">Fig. 25E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,150,969]" pageId="13" pageNumber="391">
Mature female body length 
<quantity box="[518,641,438,465]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.35" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="2.2" pageId="13" pageNumber="391" unit="mm" value="23.5" valueMax="25.0" valueMin="22.0">22–25 mm</quantity>
(n = 5). Coloration and morphology similar to male (
<figureCitation box="[1259,1345,439,465]" captionStart="FIGURE 26" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1734,1758]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,1041,1704]" captionTargetId="figure-56@15.[154,1433,1035,1710]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 26. Perlodinella epiproctalis (Zwick, 1997), female nymph. A: head and thorax, dorsal view; B–C: abdomen, dorsal and ventral view; D: sterna 8–10, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810283" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810283/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="391">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
). Wingpads length regular (
<figureCitation box="[381,486,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 26" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1734,1758]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,1041,1704]" captionTargetId="figure-56@15.[154,1433,1035,1710]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 26. Perlodinella epiproctalis (Zwick, 1997), female nymph. A: head and thorax, dorsal view; B–C: abdomen, dorsal and ventral view; D: sterna 8–10, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810283" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810283/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="391">Fig. 26A</figureCitation>
). A horizontal sclerite is present on the posterior margin of sternum 8 of female (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 26" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1734,1758]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,1041,1704]" captionTargetId="figure-56@15.[154,1433,1035,1710]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 26. Perlodinella epiproctalis (Zwick, 1997), female nymph. A: head and thorax, dorsal view; B–C: abdomen, dorsal and ventral view; D: sterna 8–10, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810283" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810283/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="391">Fig. 26D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,150,969]" pageId="13" pageNumber="391">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,255,547,573]" pageId="13" pageNumber="391">Egg:</emphasis>
General color dark brown to black. Subglobular, with three obscure longitudinal ridges. Collar slender and more sclerotized, cylindrical with a broad base. Anchor mushroom-shaped, evenly covered with small globular bodies. Each side of the egg with 5-6 short transverse row of micropyles (
<figureCitation box="[978,1062,619,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 27" captionStartId="16.[151,250,893,917]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,181,869]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[154,1434,181,869]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 27. Perlodinella epiproctalis (Zwick, 1997), egg. A: lateral view; B: top view; C: top view, anchor removed; D: sketch." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810285" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810285/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="391">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
